   1188  fc87							; Random
   1189  fc87							; --------------
   1190  fc87							; There is no such thing as Random in computers.  To simulate a random number
   1191  fc87							; it is common to use a Linear Feedback Shift Register, or LFSR for short.
   1192  fc87							; We're going to use one that's known as a Galois LFSR:
   1193  fc87							;	 http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_feedback_shift_register#Galois_LFSRs
   1194  fc87							;
   1195  fc87							; An LFSR will generate a seemingly random sequence of values, but the values
   1196  fc87							; will repeat after a while.  An 8 bit LFSR will repeat after 255 values.  A
   1197  fc87							; 16 bit LFSR will repeat after 65535 values.
   1198  fc87							;
   1199  fc87							; Fred Quimby, aka batari, wrote the routine we're using .  He posted it here:
   1200  fc87							;	 http://atariage.com/forums/topic/159268-random-numbers/?p=1958751
   1201  fc87							;
   1202  fc87							; Fred is also the create of the Harmony Cartridge, which is very handy for
   1203  fc87							; testing your program on a real Atari, as well as batari BASIC.
   1204  fc87							;   http://harmony.atariage.com/Site/Harmony.html
   1205  fc87							;   http://bataribasic.com
   1206  fc87							;
   1207  fc87							; In order to use this function you need to allocation a RAM variable called
   1208  fc87							; Rand8.  Doing just that and the code works as an 8 bit LFSR.  If you have
   1209  fc87							; some extra RAM, which isn't always feasible on the Atari, then allocating a
   1210  fc87							; second RAM variable called Rand16 will turn this into a 16 bit LFSR.
   1211  fc87							;===============================================================================
   1212  fc87				   Random
   1213  fc87		       a5 ae		      lda	Rand8
   1214  fc89		       4a		      lsr
   1215  fc8a					      ifconst	Rand16
   1216  fc8a		       26 af		      rol	Rand16	; this command is only used if Rand16 has been defined
   1217  fc8c					      endif
   1218  fc8c		       90 02		      bcc	noeor
   1219  fc8e		       49 b4		      eor	#$B4
   1220  fc90				   noeor
   1221  fc90		       85 ae		      sta	Rand8
   1222  fc92					      ifconst	Rand16
   1223  fc92		       45 af		      eor	Rand16	; this command is only used if Rand16 has been defined
   1224  fc94					      endif
